igration officials, to offer a rare perspective on the surveillance that undocumented immigrants encounter daily. He describes how and why these immigrants engage with various institutions—for example, by registering with the IRS or enrolling their kids in public health insurance programs—that the government can use to monitor them. This institutional surveillance feels both necessary and coercive, with undocumented immigrants worrying that evasion will give the government cause to deport them. Even so, they hope their record of engagement will one day help them prove to immigration officials that they deserve societal membership. Asad uncovers how these efforts do not always meet immigration officials’ high expectations, and how surveillance is as much about the threat of exclusion as the promise of inclusion.Calling attention to the fraught lives of undocumented immigrants and their families, this superbly written and compassionately argued book proposes wide-ranging, actionable reforms to achieve societal inclusion for all.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEmigration and immigrationzTexaszDallas County. 0aHispanic AmericansxCivil rights. 0aImmigrant familieszTexaszDallas County. 0aNoncitizenszTexaszDallas County. 0aSurveillance detectionzTexaszDallas County. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aAsad L. Asad.  aBooks about Surveillance and rights.  aEngage and Evade.  aHow everyday forms of surveillance threaten undocumented immigrants.  aPrinceton University Press.  aagency.  acomprehensive immigration reform.  adaily life.  adeportation.  aethnography.  aimmigration.  ainterviews.  alatinos.  alegalization.  apolicing.  apunishment.  asocial roles.  astatistics.  astorytelling.  asurveillance.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyter